[2] Canada (SK)
Date: Thu 25 Oct 2012
Source: News Talk 980 [edited]
http://cjme.com/story/measles-case-reported-saskatoon-health-region/80866


Measles case reported in Saskatoon Health Region
------------------------------------------
Measles hasn't been seen in the Saskatoon Health Region in the past 15 years, but Thursday 25 Oct 2012 the region is reporting a case of the disease. Parents of infants should check their children's vaccination records, said Julie Kryzanowski, the region's medical health officer.

About one in 4 children younger than 2 are not properly covered by the vaccine because their immunizations are not up to date, she said. "We're at about 76 per cent coverage rate for children under 2 years with 2 doses, so public health will be calling parents of children who are behind with their measles vaccine," Kryzanowski said.

"We've set up extra drop in clinics in Saskatoon and some of the surrounding communities of our health region starting Saturday [27 Oct 2012] and running through next week."

Measles can be quite serious. "If somebody isn't protected by immunization and they are exposed to a case of measles, over 90 per cent will be infected," Kryzanowski said. "Whenever we see a single case of measles we are concerned about the risk of an outbreak because measles is so contagious."

While rare, there are cases seen across the country. "Most of the cases of measles that we do see in Canada are sporadic cases and usually attributed to travel internationally or people coming from overseas to Canada and bringing the measles virus with them."

The case here has been linked to a case in Prince Albert reported last month. The case is a woman lives in one of the more rural areas of the region and began feeling the symptoms 13 Oct 2012 before being diagnosed 16 Oct 2012. The incubation period is between 7 and 21 days, so there is still a week left before the region will know for sure if anyone else was infected.

[Byline: Angela Hill]


